    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-04-03T17:15:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-04-03T17:15:00-05:00" n="39"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d39">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1–GE/4–354: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Korea</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d39fn1">Repeated for information to Canberra, London,
                        Ottawa, Paris, Tokyo, and Wellington.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-04-03T17:15:00-05:00"
                            >April 3, 1954—5:15 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>782. Secretary has authorized consultations with Commonwealth and France on
                    substantive matters Korean phase Geneva Conference. Department plans hold
                    separate meetings April 5 or 6 with <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>, then
                    Canada, Australia, New Zealand, and then France through Embassy representatives
                    Washington probably Ambassadorial level.<note n="2" xml:id="d39fn2">See telegram
                        797, Apr. 8, <ref target="#pg_80">p. 80</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>US will present as initial position on unification desirability resuming <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> unification program in <gloss target="#t_GA1"
                        >GA</gloss> Resolution October 7, 1950<note n="3" xml:id="d39fn3">Text in
                            <ref target="frus1950v07#pg_904">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1950, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">vii</hi>, p. 904</ref>.</note> as well as previous
                        <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> resolutions hold elections North Korea as
                    well as South for unifying country. <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>
                    resolutions carried out in South but prevented in North by Communist obstruction
                    and aggression. Principal advantages this position at beginning consultations
                    are: (1) backs up <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> and sacrifices of three
                    years to preserve <pb facs="0095" n="69" xml:id="pg_69"/>
                    <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> against Communists; (2) upholds <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> resolutions on Korean unification and existing
                    Commission which are still valid and operative; (3) is a good tactical position
                    because gives us room for maneuver in discussion with allies, with <gloss
                        target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> and at Conference.</p>
                <p>Inform <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName> Monday morning<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d39fn4">Apr. 5.</note> Seoul time we beginning consultations with
                    our other allies although still desire consult first with <gloss
                        target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> as indicated to him (<gloss target="#t_Deptel1"
                        >Deptel</gloss> 756 and Your 940).<note n="5" xml:id="d39fn5">Dated Mar. 24
                        and 25, <ref target="#pg_53">pp. 53</ref> and <ref target="#pg_55"
                        >55</ref>.</note> Meetings will probably be arranged for Monday or Tuesday.
                    Would be glad have any views <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName> may
                    wish make on substantive questions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
